In [[mathematics]] and [[Supersymmetric gauge theory]], '''spectral networks''' are "networks of [[Trajectory|trajectories]] on [[Riemann surface]]s obeying certain local rules. Spectral networks arise naturally in [[Four-dimensional space|four-dimensional]] ''N''&nbsp;=&nbsp;2 theories coupled to surface defects, particularly the theories of class S."<ref>{{Cite journal|arxiv=1204.4824|title= Spectral networks|journal= Annales Henri Poincaré|volume= 14|issue= 7|pages= 1643|date=|last1= Gaiotto|first1= Davide|last2=  Moore|first2= Gregory W.|last3= Neitzke|first3= Andrew|year= 2012|doi= 10.1007/s00023-013-0239-7|bibcode= 2013AnHP...14.1643G}}</ref><ref>http://hep.caltech.edu/ym35/presentations/Moore.pdf</ref>

