In mathematics, the '''Taniyama group''' is a [[Group (mathematics)|group]] that is an [[Group extension|extension]] of the [[absolute Galois group]] of the [[Rational number|rationals]] by the [[Serre group]]. It was introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Langlands|authorlink=Robert Langlands|year=1977}} using an observation by [[Deligne]], and named after [[Yutaka Taniyama]]. It was intended to be the [[group scheme]] whose representations correspond to the (hypothetical) [[Complex multiplication|CM]] [[Motive (algebraic geometry)|motives]] over the field '''Q''' of rational numbers.
==References== *{{citation|mr=0654325 |chapter=Langlands’s Construction of the Taniyama Group |last=Deligne|first= Pierre|author1-link=Pierre Deligne|last2= Milne|first2= James S.|author2-link=James Milne (mathematician)|last3= Ogus|first3= Arthur|author3-link=Arthur Ogus|last4= Shih|first4= Kuang-yen |title=Hodge cycles, motives, and Shimura varieties. |series=Lecture Notes in Mathematics|volume= 900|publisher= Springer-Verlag|place=Berlin-New York|year= 1982|isbn= 3-540-11174-3|doi=10.1007/978-3-540-38955-2_14 |url=http://www.jmilne.org/math/articles/1982c.pdf}} *{{citation|mr=0546619 |last=Langlands|first= R. P.|authorlink=Robert Langlands |chapter=Automorphic representations, Shimura varieties, and motives. Ein Märchen|title= Automorphic forms, representations and L-functions |series=Proc. Sympos. Pure Math.|pages= 205–246|volume=33|isbn=0-8218-1437-0 }}
